'''Amber Jane Butchart''' is a British fashion historian<ref name=jacobs>{{cite news|last1=Jacobs|first1=Bel|title=Amber Jane Butchart: My style can be described as art teacher meets Pat Butcher|url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/05/01/amber-jane-butchart-my-style-can-be-described-as-ghostworld-art-teacher-meets-bat-butcher-3707673/|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=Metro|date=1 May 2013}}</ref> and writer from [[Kessingland]], [[Suffolk]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chapman |first1=Thomas |title=Fashion historian set to present BBC Four documentary series |url=http://www.lowestoftjournal.co.uk/what-s-on/fashion-historian-amber-butchart-kessingland-lowestoft-bbc-documentary-1-5338407 |website=Lowestoft Journal |accessdate=8 September 2018}}</ref>.

Butchart presented the [[BBC Four]]'s ''A Stitch in Time'', a six part documentary series which "explored the lives of historical figures through the clothes they wore"<ref>{{cite web |last1=BBC |first1=Four |title=A Stitch in Time Programme Page |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09l2qzs |website=BBC |publisher=BBC |accessdate=8 September 2018}}</ref>. She also presented a segment in the BBC Documentary series ''Civilisations Stories'' entitled ''The First Refugees'' regarding the silk-weaving [[Huguenots|Huguenot]] community of [[Spitalfields]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A Stitch in Time|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09l2qzs|website=BBC Four|accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0b19p7r|title='Civilisations Stories' programme page|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>She is an associate lecturer at the [[London College of Fashion]],<ref name="lcf">{{cite web|title=Teaching staff: Amber Butchart|url=http://www.arts.ac.uk/fashion/people/teaching-staff/amber-butchart/|publisher=London College of Fashion|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> and was formerly head buyer for vintage clothing company [[Beyond Retro]].<ref name=jacobs />  She has an MA in History and Culture of Fashion from the London College of Fashion, now part of the [[University of the Arts London]].<ref name=lcf />

Butchart is a regular guest on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Women's Hour]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Women's|first1=Hour|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/search?filter=programmes&q=amber+butchart|website=BBC Radio 4}}</ref> In January 2017 she appeared on  Radio 4's ''[[The Museum of Curiosity]]'' where her hypothetical donation to this imaginary museum was "the colour [[mauve]]".<ref name="museum">{{cite web|title=The Museum of Curiosity: Series 10, Episode 3|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08b7t22|publisher=BBC Radio 4|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> She has also produced a two-part documentary for Radio 4 about the history of the vintage fashion industry entitled ''From Rags to Riches''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=BBC|first1=Radio|title=From Rags to Riches|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08nrsln|website=BBC Radio 4|publisher=BBC}}</ref>

She regularly hosts fashion events, including ''Puttin’ on the Glitz: Fashion & Film in the Jazz Age'' at the [[British Library]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tyrannyofstyle.com/puttin-on-glitz-fashion-film-jazz-age|title=Puttin' On The Glitz - Fashion & Film in the Jazz Age|first=Sophia|last=Shillito|date=21 April 2014|newspaper=Tyranny of Style: A closer look at costume design and the language of clothing.|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref>

She is one half of DJ duo Broken Hearts along with Nisha Stevens.<ref name="broken">{{cite web|title=Broken Hearts|url=http://www.thebrokenhearts.co.uk/|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref>

