The '''Coalition to Abolish the Fur Trade''' ('''CAFT''') is an informal international coalition of grassroots groups that campaign against the production and use of animal fur for clothing and other items. It started in the USA in the 1990s, when [[fur farm]]s were being raided quite regularly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nocompromise.org/issues/04furwar.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-10-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916161754/http://www.nocompromise.org/issues/04furwar.html |archivedate=2008-09-16 |df= }}</ref>
== CAFT-UK== There are several CAFT branches around the world, but the one in the [[United Kingdom]] has the biggest internet presence. As at Oct 2008, they are running a campaign against the London-based department store [[Harrods]], because it sells garments containing real fur.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://caft.org.uk/harrods/harrods.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-10-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006220619/http://www.caft.org.uk/harrods/harrods.htm |archivedate=2008-10-06 |df= }}</ref>
In 2007 CAFT-UK announced the results a two-year investigation into the use of rabbit fur. They infiltrated farms, slaughterhouses, dressing companies, manufacturers and retailers, getting photographic and video evidence of the process.<ref>http://rabbitfur.org/expose.htm</ref>
